03916nam a22005055i 9781846157561DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461575617 a10.1515/97818461575612doi  a(DE-B1597)675236  a(OCoLC)747720608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780.92qOCoLC222/eng/20230216  aGK 4480qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/41031:1 aLambert, Sterling, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRe-reading Poetry :bSchubert's Multiple Settings of Goethe /cSterling Lambert. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (292 p.) :b4 colour illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Music Examples -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Schubert the Singer -- t2. The Sea of Eternity -- t3. The River of Time -- t4. The Shape of the Moon -- t5. The Aesthetics of Genre -- tResetting, Recycling: Schubert’s Wilhelm Meister -- t6. Recycling the Harper -- t7. Recycling Mignon -- t8. One Song to the Tune of Another -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: List of Schubert’s Multiple Settings of Goethe -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most important aspects of Franz Schubert's song production has remained relatively neglected: the many occasions on which he set poetry to music more than once. This practice of returning to poems, and responding to them anew, is unusual and suggests a greater degree of literary sensitivity on the part of Schubert than is often ascribed to him. In contrast to his similarly frequent tendency to produce revised versions of songs, Schubert's resetting of poetry results in completely new songs. The presence of residues of earlier settings in later ones prompts consideration of the degree to which resettings are to some extent 'radical revisions' of their predecessors. Italso raises questions as to what those residues might signify about how and why Schubert reset poetry. Nowhere are such issues more fascinatingly and comprehensively illustrated than in Schubert's multiple settings of the poet whowas more important to him than any other: Johann Wolfgang von Goethe. In recent years, a renewed interest in the relationship between Goethe and Schubert has demonstrated that the two men had more in common than has historicallybeen supposed. A specific bond between them lies in Goethe's recognition that his poems could be read in more than one way. Re-reading Poetry uncovers an important shared outlook between composer and poet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGerman Literature. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615756140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846157561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846157561/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles